TypeScript is a programming language that builds on top of JavaScript, adding optional static typing and other features. It is designed for the development of large applications, and it helps developers catch errors early in the development process, making the code more maintainable and easier to reason about.

Duck typing, on the other hand, is a concept in object-oriented programming where an object is treated as an instance of a class if it has the same methods and properties as the class. It is often referred to as "if it looks like a duck, swims like a duck, and quacks like a duck, then it probably is a duck." In other words, the type of an object is determined by its behavior, not by its internal structure.

In TypeScript, duck typing can be achieved by using interfaces or type aliases to define the expected behavior of an object. These definitions can then be used to check whether an object has the required methods and properties at runtime.

For example, consider the following TypeScript code:
```csharp
interface Todo {
  id: number;
  title: string;
  completed: boolean;
  markAsComplete(): void;
}

const todos: Todo[] = [
  { id: 1, title: 'Buy milk', completed: false },
  { id: 2, title: 'Walk the dog', completed: true }
];

const todo = todos[0];
todo.markAsComplete();
```
In this example, we define an interface `Todo` that specifies the expected properties and methods of a Todo object. We then create an array of Todo objects and initialize them with the required properties. We can then access the `markAsComplete` method on the first Todo object and call it, knowing that it will work because it conforms to the `Todo` interface.

In summary, TypeScript allows for duck typing by using interfaces or type aliases to define the expected behavior of an object, which can then be used to check whether an object has the required methods and properties at runtime. This helps developers write more maintainable and scalable code.

To create a Discord bot using Discord.js v14 with a single slash command, `ban`, follow the steps below. First, make sure you have Node.js installed and then set up a new Discord bot project using the following command:

```bash
npm init -y
npm install discord.js@latest
```

Create a new file called `ban-bot.js` and add the following code:

```javascript
const Discord = require("discord.js");
const client = new Discord.Client();
const commands = ["ban"];

client.commands = commands;

client.on("messageCreate", async message => {
  if (message.author.bot || !message.content.startsWith(["!"])) return;

  const args = message.content
    .slice(1)
    .trim()
    .split(/ +/)
    .filter(arg => arg.length > 0);

  const command = args.shift().toLowerCase();

  if (client.commands.includes(command)) {
    try {
      await client.execute(command, args, message);
    } catch (error) {
      console.error(error);
      message.reply("Sorry, something went wrong! Please try again later.");
    }
  } else {
    message.reply("Sorry, I don't know that command!");
  }
});

client.login("YOUR_BOT_TOKEN");
```

Replace `"YOUR_BOT_TOKEN"` with your bot's token. Now, the bot will listen for slash commands, process the `ban` command, and respond accordingly.

To add the slash command, create a new file called `ban.js` in the `commands` folder, or in the same folder as `ban-bot.js`, if you haven't created a `commands` folder. Add the following code:

```javascript
const { SlashCommandBuilder } = require("discord.js");
const fs = require("fs");

module.exports = {
  data: new SlashCommandBuilder()
    .setName("ban")
    .setDescription("Ban a user.")
    .addIntegerOption((option) =>
      option.setName("userId").setDescription("User ID of the user to ban.")
    ),
  async execute(interaction) {
    const userId = interaction.options.getInteger("userId");
    if (!userId) {
      return interaction.reply({
        content: "Please provide a user ID.",
        ephemeral: true,
      });
    }

    const user = interaction.guild.members.cache.find(
      (member) => member.id === userId
    );

    if (!user) {
      return interaction.reply({
        content: "User not found.",
        ephemeral: true,
      });
    }

    await user.guild.bans.add(user.id);
    await interaction.reply({
      content: `Successfully banned ${user.user.username} (${user.id})`,
      ephemeral: true,
    });
    fs.appendFile("logs.txt", `${Date().toLocaleString()} - User ${user.user.username} (${user.id}) was banned.\n`);
  },
};
